# ============================================================================
# Python bytecode cache.
# When Python runs a .py file, it compiles it to bytecode and stores the
# result in a __pycache__/ folder next to the source (e.g.
# bookMng/__pycache__/views.cpython-313.pyc). The contents are auto-
# generated, machine- and Python-version-specific, and regenerated on every
# run. There is no reason to commit them.
# ============================================================================
__pycache__/
*.pyc
*.pyo

# ============================================================================
# Django development database.
# SQLite stores all app data (users, books, ratings, comments, sessions) in
# this single file. Committing it causes two recurring headaches:
#   1. Merge conflicts on a binary file whenever two people's local data
#      diverges.
#   2. "table already exists" errors when the committed schema drifts from
#      the tracked migration files (exactly what bit us with the rating
#      table — see README.md).
# Each developer should rebuild their own local DB from migrations with:
#     python manage.py migrate
# ----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# Note: this line only prevents *new* untracked db.sqlite3 files from being
# added. The version already committed in git stays tracked until someone
# runs `git rm --cached db.sqlite3` and commits that removal. README.md
# walks through that one-time cleanup.
# ============================================================================
db.sqlite3
db.sqlite3-journal

# ============================================================================
# PyCharm / IntelliJ per-user state.
# The .idea/ folder mixes useful shared config (module definition, run
# configurations) with files that change every time you open, scroll, or
# click anything in the IDE. We track the shared config but ignore the
# churn-y ones below. workspace.xml is the biggest offender — it logs your
# window layout, open tabs, cursor positions, and which files you recently
# searched; committing it produces noisy diffs and meaningless conflicts.
# ============================================================================
.idea/workspace.xml
.idea/shelf/
.idea/usage.statistics.xml
.idea/dictionaries/
.idea/jsLibraryMappings.xml
.idea/tasks.xml
.idea/contentModel.xml
.idea/dataSources.local.xml
.idea/httpRequests/

# ============================================================================
# Python virtual environments, in case anyone creates one locally instead of
# using Anaconda base. These are multi-hundred-megabyte folders of installed
# packages — never commit them; `requirements.txt` is the portable version.
# ============================================================================
venv/
env/
.venv/
ENV/

# ============================================================================
# OS-generated junk files.
# Windows creates Thumbs.db for folder thumbnails; macOS creates .DS_Store
# for Finder state. Neither belongs in a code repo.
# ============================================================================
Thumbs.db
.DS_Store

# ============================================================================
# Harness directories for AI dev tools (Claude Code worktrees, etc.).
# These are scratch workspaces the tools create for themselves; contents
# are isolated from the main project.
# ============================================================================
.claude/
